Background

Influenza vaccine effectiveness: addressing missing data by multiple imputation

An observational study investigated the effect of influenza vaccination on influenza infection in the general population. To estimate the vaccine effect, potential confounding effects and effect modification will be considered. Data are available from 2000 adults aged 20 to 60y (saved in ‘fluvaccine.csv’), with the following variables:

Missing dataset (MCAR)

a Study missingness

Dataset with missing data (MCAR)

  1. Suppose the same dataset have some missing data (‘fluvaccine_m1.csv’). Study the dataset especially on the missingness of the data.
  1. aggr()
    Calculate or plot the amount of missing/imputed values in each variable and the amount of missing/imputed values in certain combinations of variables
  2. marginplot()
    In addition to a standard scatterplot, information about missing/imputed values is shown in the plot margins. Furthermore, imputed vlaues are highlighted in the scatterplot.
  3. complete.cases()
    Return a logcial vector indicating which cases are complte, i.e. have no missing values.

Answer 

flu.m1 <- read.csv('Data/fluvaccine_m1.csv')

## Summary function
summary(flu.m1) # missing data in shealth, smoking, vac and flu => see NA in these variables indicating missingness

## 1 Visualize missing pattern `aggr()`  
require(VIM)
aggr_plot <- aggr(flu.m1, sortVars=T, numbers=T) 

#If no “sortvars=T”, it will not sort variables by number of missingness
#LHS: 4 variable hv 10% missing; RHS graph means the missingness of combination of variables where blue cell means complete data; 

## 2 Visualize missing pattern `marginplot()`  
#colnames(flu.m1) to check variable names

marginplot(flu.m1[,c(4,5)]) # shealth and smoking  

#Margin plot for 4th and 5th variables) 
#=> note boxplot for complete data (blue) and missing data (red) for self rated health
#=> only 0 and 1 for smoking so can't see anything
quantile(flu.m1$shealth[is.na(flu.m1$smoking)],na.rm=T) #range of self rated health with smoking missing
quantile(flu.m1$shealth[!is.na(flu.m1$smoking)],na.rm=T) #range of self rated health with smoking not missing
#Can see that median are the same but not IQR — consistent with the box plot

marginplot(flu.m1[,c(4,7)]) # shealth and vac

#Self rated health score is exactly the same shown from box-plot
#Vaccination status is binomial,  and no box plot is formed if large enough dataset that data located on either 1 or 0. 
#Thus a weird  box-plot formed for missing data coz only 10% missingness (not enough dataset). None for complete data (enough dataset). This is shown in quantile too.
quantile(flu.m1$vac[is.na(flu.m1$shealth)],na.rm=T)
quantile(flu.m1$vac[!is.na(flu.m1$shealth)],na.rm=T)

## 3 Return T and F abt missingness `complete.cases()`  
flu.m1$complete <- complete.cases(flu.m1)
head(flu.m1) #False is when there is missing data, e.g. the first row
prop.table(table(flu.m1$complete)) # 66% of the records are complete cases

#Box plot for continuous variable; Proportion table for discrete variable
boxplot(shealth~complete, data=flu.m1) #Distribution of self rated health in complete and missing data is quite similar

with(flu.m1, prop.table(table(vac, complete),2)) #2 = by column. Distribution of vaccination status in complete and missing data also quite similar
#fisher.test(with(flu.m1, table(vac, complete)))
with(flu.m1, prop.table(table(smoking, complete),2))
#fisher.test(with(flu.m1, table(smoking, complete)))

b CCA

Complete case analysis

  1. It was known that missingness was completely random (MCAR). Carry out a complete case analysis and compare the results with that in (a).

Answer 

lr0.m1 <- glm(flu~vac+shealth+vac*smoking, data=flu.m1, family=binomial) #note 683 observations deleted
summary(lr0.m1)

cbind(exp(coef(lr0.m1)),exp(confint(lr0.m1)))

ci MI: Construct dataset + check whether imputed sensibly

Construct imputed dataset using variables in the final analysis model

  1. To deal with missing data, multiple imputation method will be used. Create the imputed datasets (say, 50 imputations), based on the variables in the final analysis model. Assess if the variables were imputed sensibly by examining the imputed variables and comparing them with the original dataset.
### Multiple imputation
require(Hmisc)
## Transcan
set.seed(111) #so that output is reproducible in future
flu.m1.impute <- transcan(~flu+vac+shealth+smoking, n.impute=50,
                          shrink=T, data=flu.m1, imputed=T)

flu.m1.impute$imputed$shealth[,1] #1st imputed dataset (50 in total) showing shealth
flu.m1.impute$imputed$vac[,1]

## Switch to aregImpute
set.seed(11)
flu.m1.impute <- aregImpute(~flu+vac+shealth+smoking, n.impute=50, data=flu.m1)
flu.m1.impute$imputed$shealth[,1]
flu.m1.impute$imputed$vac[,1]

### Visualize imputed data
## shealth (numeric variable)
boxplot(flu.m1$shealth, border='blue', at=1, xlim=c(0,3)) #distribution of origianl dataset shealth
boxplot(flu.m1.impute$imputed$shealth[,1], border='red', at=2, add=T) #distribution of 1st imputed dataset shealth

boxplot(flu.m1$shealth, border='blue', at=1, xlim=c(0,53))
for (i in 1:50) boxplot(flu.m1.impute$imputed$shealth[,i], border='red', at=i+1, add=T) #distribution of 50 imputed dataset shealth

#The median and IQR are quite similar (compare blue and red)

## vac (categorical)
prop.table(table(flu.m1$vac))
prop.table(table(flu.m1.impute$imputed$vac[,1]))
for(i in 1:50) print(prop.table(table(flu.m1.impute$imputed$vac[,i])))
#Porportion of vaccination didn't fluctuate a lot, quite similar (~23%)

Multiple imputation using variables in the final model

  1. Perform the regression analysis using multiple imputation method. Compare your results with those in (c) and (g).

Answer 

### Multiple imputation
## aregImpute
set.seed(1)
flu.m2.impute <- aregImpute(~flu+vac+shealth+smoking, n.impute=50, data=flu.m2)
flu.m2.impute$imputed$vac

### Visualize imputed data
## shealth
boxplot(flu.m2$shealth, border='blue', at=1, xlim=c(0,3)) #distribution of origianl dataset shealth
boxplot(flu.m2.impute$imputed$shealth[,1], border='red', at=2, add=T) #distribution of 1st imputed dataset shealth

boxplot(flu.m2$shealth, border='blue', at=1, xlim=c(0,53))
for (i in 1:50) boxplot(flu.m2.impute$imputed$shealth[,i], border='red', at=i+1, add=T) #distribution of 50 imputed dataset shealth

#Imputation is reasonable

## vac
prop.table(table(flu$vac))
prop.table(table(flu.m2$vac))
prop.table(table(flu.m2.impute$imputed$vac[,1])) #propotion of vaccination in 1st imputed dataset
for(i in 1:50) print(prop.table(table(flu.m2.impute$imputed$vac[,i]))) #propotion of vaccination in 50 imputed dataset

### Comparing the distribution of vaccination for different shealth score, original vs imputed dataset -- skipped in lecture
#distribution of vaccination for different shealth score in original dataset
prop.table(table(flu.m2$shealth, flu.m2$vac),1) 

#distribution of vaccination for different shealth score in imputed dataset
vac.miss.m2 <- which(is.na(flu.m2$vac)) #which vac is missing
shealth.miss.m2 <- which(is.na(flu.m2$shealth)) #which shealth is missing
imputed.shealth.m2.i1 <- flu.m2$shealth #copy shealth column
imputed.shealth.m2.i1[shealth.miss.m2] <- flu.m2.impute$imputed$shealth[,1] #replace missing shealth with shealth from 1st imputed dataset
prop.table(table(imputed.shealth.m2.i1[vac.miss.m2], flu.m2.impute$imputed$vac[,1]),1) #shealth where vac is missing AGAINST vac from 1st imputed dataset

Interpretation of results

  • The estimate for “flu vaccination × current smoker” is consistent in CCA (b) and MI with more variables (d), therefore, MI with more variables (d) is more reliable than MI (c).

  1. Perform the regression analysis again using multiple imputation method. Compare your results with those in (c) and (h).

Answer 

### Complete case analysis
lr0.m3 <- glm(flu~vac+shealth+vac*smoking, data=flu.m3, family=binomial)
summary(lr0.m3)

cbind(exp(coef(lr0.m3)),exp(confint(lr0.m3)))
#Very wide 95%CI coz lots of missing data (unreasonble estimate)

### MI with all variables
## Construct dataset
set.seed(2)
flu.m3.impute <- aregImpute(~flu+vac+shealth+smoking+age+male+bmi+abT, n.impute=50, data=flu.m3)
